Hey Curtis, I am not an investor, I'm an entrepreneur. One bit of advice I have though, a surgical approach is very necessary to successfully fundraise - Not a shotgun approach. Do some deeper research, find investors that specifically fit the benefits / SaaS space / are actively investing, and write a note about why this opportunity fits for them. I'm sure most of your emails are being ignored. You're doing it wrong. Instead message like 5-10 people at a time and craft a very specific intro, "Hey I see you spent the last 20 years of your career in employee benefits, I think I'm building something you'd be passionate about." Hope that helps! Good luck!

Hi Curtis: I appreciate you reaching out, and I've reviewed the deck. Naturally I have some questions and concerns. Here are a few: In terms of team qualities for seed funding, it is important that you and your team can display specific characteristics. Evolving from a pre-seed team, a seed stage funding team should be able to illustrate that it can grow fast with a close-knit group that can work fast depending on new  insights. It is also critical to have a strong vision for the product. Furthermore, it is important to prove that the business can get people on-side (this includes customers, partners, and employees). This displays that other people and professionals have faith in your product. When it comes to the product of the business, at the seed stage, it is crucial to demonstrate that it is well-liked by early users as this shows viability in the business. Adding on from=C2=A0 this, it should also have fantastic engagement, and there should also be a powerful strategy present on how to break into a large Total Addressable Market (TAM) over some time. Remember, at this funding stage, it is important to prove to the investors that your business is the future and worth investing in. At the seed funding stage, there should already be natural traction for the business and evidence of success with you (founder)-leading sales. Founder-led sales are when the companys founder connects with leads they have found and helps them trial the product. The founder then transforms these leads and signs them up for paid plans. A further requirement for seed funding is that you can demonstrate capital efficiency through true resourcefulness and that your lean team (4 of you) can still get many things completed with just a small team. This helps reassure us investors that the founder is capable and frugal. As with pre-seed funding, the moat for a seed stage company is its fantastic ideas. It seems to me that you're quite a bit over your ski's. I you don't yet have PMF, I don't think you should be spending $600K to bring in additional employees. How much have you raised so far? At what valuation are you hoping to be post money. Seems like your still in the Pre-Seed stage and should be raising around a million. Whatever amount you do raise, in todays climate, i strongly encourage you to raise 24 months at minimum. Its BRUTAL out there.Did you see the article in Tech Crunch on Stripes down round of like 50% and they are profitable w/$12B in ARR. I could have a chat next Wed or Thursday from 11-11:45am PST. LMK if you can make it work. My best,
